SIMPLE: alluvion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Alluvion
<hw>Al*lu"vi*on</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>alluvion</ets>, L. <ets>alluvio</ets>, fr. <ets>alluere</ets> to
wash against; <ets>ad</ets> + <ets>luere</ets>, equiv. to
<ets>lavare</ets>, to wash. See <er>Lave</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Wash or flow of water against the shore or bank.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An overflowing; an inundation; a flood.</def>
<rj><au>Lyell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Matter deposited by an inundation or the action of
flowing water; alluvium.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The golden <qex>alluvions</qex> are there [in California and
Australia] spread over a far wider space: they are found not only on the
banks of rivers, and in their beds, but are scattered over the surface
of vast plains.</q> <rj><qau>R. Cobden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An accession of land gradually
washed to the shore or bank by the flowing of water. See
<er>Accretion</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Alluvious</ent>⟦br⟧
